8. capite et fortunis : the caput was properly the legal status or personality of a Roman, and included the rights of citizenship and of frcedom as well as the right to live. As a rule the quaestiones could not inflict the death penalty, so that the highest deminutio capitis possible would be loss of citizenship by voluntary exile. Under the Cornelian law the ancient death penalty of the “ sack '’ was retained, but only where the accused confessed his guilt. ‘Thus it would seem that Roscius was fighting for his rights as a

citizen, not for his property (which was already lost, there being no question of restitution); the addition of fortunis is merely due to the fact that capnt et fortunae was a hackneyed expression : loss

, of property was a usual accompaniment of loss of status, but in this case the meaning of fortunae is not to be pressed. See Introd., ἓ 8.
